{"title_page": "Bassa script", "text_new": "{{Short description|writing system}}\n{{Infobox writing system\n |name      = Bassa vah\n |sample    =\n |caption   =\n |imagesize =\n |type      = \n |languages = \n |time      = \n |fam1=\n |fam2=\n |fam3=\n |sisters=\n |children=\n |unicode  = [https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U16AD0.pdf U+16AD0 &ndash; U+16AFF]<br />\n[https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2010/10382r-n3941r-bassavah.pdf Final&nbsp;Accepted&nbsp;Script&nbsp;Proposal]\n |iso15924 = Bass\n |note     = none\n }}\n\n[[File:Escritura bassa vah.png|thumb|350px|The Bassa vah alphabet.]]\nThe '''Bassa script''', known as ''Bassa vah'' or simply ''vah'' ('throwing a sign' in [[Bassa language|Bassa]]) is an [[alphabet]]ic script for writing the [[Bassa language]] of [[Liberia]].  It was reinvented by {{nobr|Dr. Thomas Flo Lewis}}, who rediscovered the script in South America from descendants of Bassa Slaves taken to the Americas he  instigated publishing of limited materials in the language from the mid-1900s through the 1930s, with its height in the 1910s and 1920s. It is alleged that some of the signs are based on native Bassa pictograms revealed by a former slave. It is not clear what connection it may have had with neighboring scripts, but [[Sort (typesetting)|type]] was cast for it, and an association for its promotion was formed in Liberia in 1959. It is not used contemporarily and has been classified as a failed script.<ref>Unseth, Peter. 2011. Invention of Scripts in West Africa for Ethnic Revitalization. In ''The Success-Failure Continuum in Language and Ethnic Identity Efforts'', ed. by Joshua A. Fishman and Ofelia Garc\u00eda, pp. 23-32. New York: Oxford University Press.</ref> Its creation should be distinguished from other orthographic attempts in the 1830s by European missionaries.\n\n''Vah'' is a true alphabet, with 23 consonant letters, 7 vowel letters, and 5 tone [[diacritic]]s, which are placed inside the vowels. It also has its own marks for commas and periods.\n\n==Unicode==\n{{Main|Bassa Vah (Unicode block)}}\nThe Bassa alphabet was added to the [[Unicode]] Standard in June 2014 with the release of version 7.0.\n\nThe Unicode block for the Bassa alphabet is U+16AD0&ndash;U+16AFF:\n\n{{Unicode chart Bassa Vah}}\n\n==References==\n*Coulmas (1999) ''The Blackwell Encyclopedia of Writing Systems''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.endangeredalphabets.net/alphabets/bassa-vah/ Bassa Vah - Atlas of Endangered Alphabets]\n*[http://www.omniglot.com/writing/bassa.htm Omniglot.com]\n*Proof of some of the origins [https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2010/10382r-n3941r-bassavah.pdf]\n\nwww.yinda.de/bassa/script_history.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassa Script}}\n[[Category:Bassa language]]\n[[Category:Writing systems of Africa]]\n[[Category:Scripts with ISO 15924 four-letter codes]]\n[[Category:Scripts encoded in Unicode]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|writing system}}\n{{Infobox writing system\n |name      = Bassa vah\n |sample    =\n |caption   =\n |imagesize =\n |type      = \n |languages = \n |time      = \n |fam1=\n |fam2=\n |fam3=\n |sisters=\n |children=\n |unicode  = [https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U16AD0.pdf U+16AD0 &ndash; U+16AFF]<br />\n[https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2010/10382r-n3941r-bassavah.pdf Final&nbsp;Accepted&nbsp;Script&nbsp;Proposal]\n |iso15924 = Bass\n |note     = none\n }}\n\n[[File:Escritura bassa vah.png|thumb|350px|The Bassa vah alphabet.]]\nThe '''Bassa script''', known as ''Bassa vah'' or simply ''vah'' ('throwing a sign' in [[Bassa language|Bassa]]) is an [[alphabet]]ic script for writing the [[Bassa language]] of [[Liberia]].  It was reinvented by {{nobr|Dr. Thomas Flo Lewis}}, who rediscovered the script in South America from descendants of Bassa Slaves taken to the Americas he  instigated publishing of limited materials in the language from the mid-1900s through the 1930s, with its height in the 1910s and 1920s. It is alleged that some of the signs are based on native Bassa pictograms revealed by a former slave. It is not clear what connection it may have had with neighboring scripts, but [[Sort (typesetting)|type]] was cast for it, and an association for its promotion was formed in Liberia in 1959. It is not used contemporarily and has been classified as a failed script.<ref>Unseth, Peter. 2011. Invention of Scripts in West Africa for Ethnic Revitalization. In ''The Success-Failure Continuum in Language and Ethnic Identity Efforts'', ed. by Joshua A. Fishman and Ofelia Garc\u00eda, pp. 23-32. New York: Oxford University Press.</ref> Its creation should be distinguished from other orthographic attempts in the 1830s by European missionaries.\n\n''Vah'' is a true alphabet, with 23 consonant letters, 7 vowel letters, and 5 tone [[diacritic]]s, which are placed inside the vowels. It also has its own marks for commas and periods.\n\n==Unicode==\n{{Main|Bassa Vah (Unicode block)}}\nThe Bassa alphabet was added to the [[Unicode]] Standard in June 2014 with the release of version 7.0.\n\nThe Unicode block for the Bassa alphabet is U+16AD0&ndash;U+16AFF:\n\n{{Unicode chart Bassa Vah}}\n\n==References==\n*Coulmas (1999) ''The Blackwell Encyclopedia of Writing Systems''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.omniglot.com/writing/bassa.htm Omniglot.com]\n*Proof of some of the origins [https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2010/10382r-n3941r-bassavah.pdf]\n\nwww.yinda.de/bassa/script_history.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bassa Script}}\n[[Category:Bassa language]]\n[[Category:Writing systems of Africa]]\n[[Category:Scripts with ISO 15924 four-letter codes]]\n[[Category:Scripts encoded in Unicode]]\n", "name_user": "Yeonjikang", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added an external link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bassa_script"}
{"title_page": "Gadabas", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Gadaba inde 02 05.jpg|thumb|right|A Gadaba woman in traditional attire]]\n[[File:Crafts Museum New Delhi 3 Sep 2010-8.JPG|thumb|right|A traditional Gadaba hut]]\nThe '''Gadabas''' are an ethnic group of eastern [[India]]. They are a designated [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Tribe]] in [[Odisha]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |pages=21\u201322 |title=List of notified Scheduled Tribes |publisher=Census India |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107225208/http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |archivedate=7 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThere are 84,689 Gadabas in Odisha and 38,081 in Andhra Pradesh as per the 2011 Indian census.<ref name=\"census\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/ST.html|title=A-11 Individual Scheduled Tribe Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix|website=www.censusindia.gov.in|publisher=Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref> The subgroups of Gadaba are Bada Gadaba, Sana Gadaba, Gutab Gadaba, Farenga Gadaba and Allar Gadaba. Their socioeconomic life is based on farming and daily labour. They are involved in both [[Slash-and-burn]] and plow cultivation. They live in permanent villages. They are well known for their tribal dance, the [[Dhemsa]]. The Gadabas speak [[Gutob language|Gutob]] and [[Ollari language|Ollari]], which are Austroasiatic and Dravidian languages respectively. Since the early 1980s the Gadabas have largely been displaced from their villages by the building of hydro-electric dams and the resulting lakes.\n\nGadaba women traditionally wear neck rings which are about 500-700 grams each and can not be removed without the help of a blacksmith. As a part of their tradition, it is only removed after their death. A Gadaba woman traditionally wears a two-piece dress which is very colorful, often striped in red, blue and white, which is woven by the women themselves. The ornaments they wear are not very different from those of other tribes\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n*http://www.india9.com/i9show/Gadabas-29991.htm\n*https://books.google.com/books?id=aRSOnRfPAq0C&pg=PA82\n*http://ingetjetadros.com/\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.endangeredalphabets.net/alphabets/gadaba/ Gadaba - Atlas of Endangered Alphabets]\n* Philipose Vaidyar  http://pvarticles.blogspot.com/2011/06/lets-go-and-get-on-with-gadaba.html\n\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Andhra Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Gadaba inde 02 05.jpg|thumb|right|A Gadaba woman in traditional attire]]\n[[File:Crafts Museum New Delhi 3 Sep 2010-8.JPG|thumb|right|A traditional Gadaba hut]]\nThe '''Gadabas''' are an ethnic group of eastern [[India]]. They are a designated [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Tribe]] in [[Odisha]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |pages=21\u201322 |title=List of notified Scheduled Tribes |publisher=Census India |accessdate=15 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107225208/http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/ST%20Lists.pdf |archivedate=7 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThere are 84,689 Gadabas in Odisha and 38,081 in Andhra Pradesh as per the 2011 Indian census.<ref name=\"census\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/ST.html|title=A-11 Individual Scheduled Tribe Primary Census Abstract Data and its Appendix|website=www.censusindia.gov.in|publisher=Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref> The subgroups of Gadaba are Bada Gadaba, Sana Gadaba, Gutab Gadaba, Farenga Gadaba and Allar Gadaba. Their socioeconomic life is based on farming and daily labour. They are involved in both [[Slash-and-burn]] and plow cultivation. They live in permanent villages. They are well known for their tribal dance, the [[Dhemsa]]. The Gadabas speak [[Gutob language|Gutob]] and [[Ollari language|Ollari]], which are Austroasiatic and Dravidian languages respectively. Since the early 1980s the Gadabas have largely been displaced from their villages by the building of hydro-electric dams and the resulting lakes.\n\nGadaba women traditionally wear neck rings which are about 500-700 grams each and can not be removed without the help of a blacksmith. As a part of their tradition, it is only removed after their death. A Gadaba woman traditionally wears a two-piece dress which is very colorful, often striped in red, blue and white, which is woven by the women themselves. The ornaments they wear are not very different from those of other tribes\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n*http://www.india9.com/i9show/Gadabas-29991.htm\n*https://books.google.com/books?id=aRSOnRfPAq0C&pg=PA82\n*http://ingetjetadros.com/\n\n== External links ==\n{{| }}\n\n[[Category:Scheduled Tribes of Andhra Pradesh]]\nPhilipose Vaidyar  http://pvarticles.blogspot.com/2011/06/lets-go-and-get-on-with-gadaba.html\n", "name_user": "Yeonjikang", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added an external link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gadabas"}
{"title_page": "Hanifi Rohingya script", "text_new": "{{Infobox writing system\n| name = Hanifi Rohingya script\n| altname = \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd07\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd15\ud803\udd1e\ud803\udd09\ud803\udd1e \ud803\udd13\ud803\udd20\ud803\udd11\ud803\udd24\ud803\udd1d<ref name=omniglot />\n| languages = [[Rohingya language]]\n| type = Alphabet\n| unicode = [https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U10D00.pdf U+10D00\u2013U+10D3F]\n| iso15924 = Rohg\n| sample =\n| note =\n}}\n\nThe '''Hanifi Rohingya script''' is a unified script for the [[Rohingya language]]. Rohingya was first written in the 19th century with a version of the [[Arabic script|Perso-Arabic script]]. In 1975, an orthographic Arabic script was developed, based on the [[Urdu alphabet]].\n\nIn the 1980s, [[Mohammad Hanif (scholar)|Mohammad Hanif]] and his colleagues created the suitable [[phonetic script]] based on Arabic letters; it has been compared to the [[N\u2019ko]] script. The script also includes a set of decimal numbers.<ref name=\"omniglot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.omniglot.com/writing/rohingya.htm|title=Rohingya alphabets, pronunciation and language|website=[[Omniglot]]|publisher=Simon Ager|access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://skyknowledge.com/rohingya.htm |title=Hanifi alphabet for Rohingya |last=James |first=Ian |date=5 July 2012 |website=Sky Knowledge |publisher= |access-date=9 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Keyboard===\n[[File:Rohingya-Keyboard-online.jpg|thumb|375px|Layout of the Rohingya virtual keyboard.]]\nA virtual keyboard was developed by [[Google]] for the Rohingya language in 2019 and allows users to type directly in the Rohingya script. The Rohingya Unicode keyboard layout can be found [https://languagetools-153419.appspot.com/rhg/ here].\n\n==Character==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Rohingya alphabets -29\n|-\n! colspan=6 | \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd09\ud803\udd22<ref>{{Cite web | title=Rohingya Language Academy | url=https://www.rohingyazuban.com/}}</ref>\n|-\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd05||\ud803\udd04||\ud803\udd03||\ud803\udd02||\ud803\udd01||\ud803\udd00\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd0b||\ud803\udd0a||\ud803\udd09||\ud803\udd08||\ud803\udd07||\ud803\udd06      \n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd11||\ud803\udd10||\ud803\udd0f||\ud803\udd0e||\ud803\udd0d||\ud803\udd0c\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd17||\ud803\udd16||\ud803\udd15||\ud803\udd14||\ud803\udd13||\ud803\udd12\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| ||\ud803\udd1c||\ud803\udd1b||\ud803\udd1a||\ud803\udd19||\ud803\udd18 \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Rohingya vowels -7\n|-\n! colspan=6 | \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd00\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd09\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c \ud803\udd00\ud803\udd1e\ud803\udd09\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd22<ref>{{Cite web | title=Rohingya Zuban | url=https://www.rohingyazuban.com/}}</ref>\n|- \n|-align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd22||\ud803\udd21||\ud803\udd20||\ud803\udd1f||\ud803\udd1e||\ud803\udd1d\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| ||\u25cc\ud803\udd27||\u25cc\ud803\udd26||\u25cc\ud803\udd25||\u25cc\ud803\udd24||\ud803\udd23       \n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Rohingya numerals\n|-\n! colspan=10 | \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd13\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd14\ud803\udd01\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd22<ref>{{Cite web | title=Rohingya Zuban Academy |