lign=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\">\u25cc\ud803\udd24</span>\n| HARBAHAY\n| '''Tone signs:''' short high tone\n| /h\u0101rb\u0101y/\n| U+10D24\n|-\n| align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\">\ud803\udd20</span>\n| ''e-for''\n| E\n| /e/\n| U+10D20\n| align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\">\u25cc\ud803\udd25</span>\n| TAHALA\n| '''Tone signs:''' long falling tone\n| /\u1e6del\u0101/\n| U+10D25\n|-\n| align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\">\ud803\udd21</span>\n| ''o-for''\n| O\n| /o/\n| U+10D21\n| align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\">\u25cc\ud803\udd26</span>\n| TANA\n| '''Tone signs:''' long rising tone\n| /\u1e6d\u0101n\u0101/\n| U+10D26\n|-\n| align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\">\u25cc\ud803\udd27</span>\n| TASSI\n| Germination sign\n| /tassi/\n| U+10D27\n|}\n\n====Numerals====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=11 | \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd13\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd14\ud803\udd01\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd22\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:150%;\"></span>\n! Name\n| sifir||ek||dui||tin||sair||fa\u00f1s||so||ha\u00f1t||a\u00f1ctho||no\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:150%;\"></span>\n! Digit\n| \ud803\udd30 || \ud803\udd31 || \ud803\udd32 || \ud803\udd33 || \ud803\udd34 || \ud803\udd35 || \ud803\udd36 || \ud803\udd37 || \ud803\udd38 || \ud803\udd39\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:130%;\"></span>\n!Unicode\n|U+10D30\n|U+10D31\n|U+10D32\n|U+10D33\n|U+10D34\n|U+10D35\n|U+10D36\n|U+10D37\n|U+10D38\n|U+10D39\n|}\n\n== Unicode ==\n{{main|Hanifi Rohingya (Unicode block)}}\n\nThe Hanifi Rohingya script was added to the [[Unicode|Unicode Standard]] in June 2018 with the release of version 11.0. Proposals to include it in Unicode were written by linguist Anshuman Pandey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unicode.org/L2/L2015/15278-hanifi-rohingya.pdf|title=Proposal to encode the Hanifi Rohingya script in Unicode|last=Pandey|first=Anshuman|date=27 October 2015|website=The Unicode Consortium|publisher=|access-date=9 October 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe Unicode block for Hanifi Rohingya is U+10D00\u2013U+10D3F and contains 50 characters:<ref>{{Cite web | title=Unicode 11.0.0 | url=https://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode11.0.0/ | publisher=[[Unicode Consortium]] | date=5 June 2018 | access-date=5 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\n{{Unicode chart Hanifi Rohingya}}\n\n==Fonts==\nGoogle's Noto Sans has developed a Rohingya script font called Noto Sans Hanifi Rohingya. Download here: [https://github.com/googlefonts/noto-fonts/tree/master/phaseIII_only/unhinted/ttf/NotoSansHanifiRohingya Noto Sans Rohingya]\n\n==HTML code tables==\n\n{|border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"8\" width=\"500\" align=left style=\"text-align:center;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=6 |Rohingya alphabets - \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd09\ud803\udd22\n|-\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd05||\ud803\udd04||\ud803\udd03||\ud803\udd02||\ud803\udd01||\ud803\udd00\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n| &amp;#x10D05;||&amp;#x10D04;||&amp;#x10D03;||&amp;#x10D02;||&amp;#x10D01;||&amp;#x10D00;\t\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd0b||\ud803\udd0a||\ud803\udd09||\ud803\udd08||\ud803\udd07||\ud803\udd06  \n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n| &amp;#x10D0B;||&amp;#x10D0A;||&amp;#x10D09;||&amp;#x10D08;||&amp;#x10D07;||&amp;#x10D06;\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd11||\ud803\udd10||\ud803\udd0f||\ud803\udd0e||\ud803\udd0d||\ud803\udd0c\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n| &amp;#x10D11;||&amp;#x10D10;||&amp;#x10D0F;||&amp;#x10D0E;||&amp;#x10D0D;||&amp;#x10D0C;\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd17||\ud803\udd16||\ud803\udd15||\ud803\udd14||\ud803\udd13||\ud803\udd12\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n| &amp;#x10D17;||&amp;#x10D16;||&amp;#x10D15;||&amp;#x10D14;||&amp;#x10D13;||&amp;#x10D12;\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| ||\ud803\udd1c||\ud803\udd1b||\ud803\udd1a||\ud803\udd19||\ud803\udd18 \n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n| ||&amp;#x10D1C;||&amp;#x10D1B;||&amp;#x10D1A;||&amp;#x10D19;||&amp;#x10D18;\n|}{{clear}}\n\n{|border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"8\" width=\"500\" align=left style=\"text-align:center;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=6 |Rohingya vowels - \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd00\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd09\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c \ud803\udd00\ud803\udd1e\ud803\udd09\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd22\n|- \n|-align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd22||\ud803\udd21||\ud803\udd20||\ud803\udd1f||\ud803\udd1e||\ud803\udd1d\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n| &amp;#x10D22;||&amp;#x10D21;||&amp;#x10D20;||&amp;#x10D1F;||&amp;#x10D1E;||&amp;#x10D1D;\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| ||\u25cc\ud803\udd27||\u25cc\ud803\udd26||\u25cc\ud803\udd25||\u25cc\ud803\udd24||\ud803\udd23  \n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n|||&amp;#x10D27;||&amp;#x10D26;||&amp;#x10D25;||&amp;#x10D24;||&amp;#x10D23;     \n|}{{clear}}\n\n{|border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"8\" width=\"500\" align=left style=\"text-align:center;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=10 |Rohingya numerals - \ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd1f\ud803\udd07\ud803\udd25\ud803\udd1d\ud803\udd1a\ud803\udd12\ud803\udd19\ud803\udd1d \ud803\udd13\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd14\ud803\udd01\ud803\udd21\ud803\udd0c\ud803\udd22\n|-\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:200%;\"></span>\n| \ud803\udd30 || \ud803\udd31 || \ud803\udd32 || \ud803\udd33 || \ud803\udd34 || \ud803\udd35 || \ud803\udd36 || \ud803\udd37 || \ud803\udd38 || \ud803\udd39\n|- align=center | <span style=\"font-size:90%;\"></span>\n| &amp;#x10D30;||&amp;#x10D31;||&amp;#x10D32;||&amp;#x10D33;||&amp;#x10D34;||&amp;#x10D35;||&amp;#x10D36;||&amp;#x10D37;||&amp;#x10D38;||&amp;#x10D39;\n|}{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Rohingya people]]\n[[Category:Alphabets]]\n[[Category:Writing systems of Asia]]\n[[Category:Writing systems introduced in 1980]]\n[[Category:Scripts encoded in Unicode]]\n[[Category:Arabic script]]\n\n\n{{writingsystem-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Yeonjikang", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added an external link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanifi_Rohingya_script"}
{"title_page": "Lampung language", "text_new": "{{short description|Language in Indonesia}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Lampung\n|nativename=''cawa Lampung''{{sfn|Aliana|1986|p=39}}\n|states=[[Indonesia]]\n|region=[[Lampung]]<br>[[South Sumatra]]\n|ethnicity=[[Lampung people]]<br>[[Komering people]]\n|speakers={{sigfig|1.477|2}} million\n|date=2000 census\n|ref={{efn|Combined figure of all dialects from ''[[Ethnologue]]''.<ref>{{e22|ljp|Lampung Api}}; {{e22|abl|Lampung Nyo}}; {{e22|kge|Komering}}</ref>}}\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[Western Indonesian languages|Western Indonesian]]?\n|dialects=[[Lampung Api|Api/Pesisir]]<br />[[Lampung Nyo|Nyo/Abung]]<br />[[Komering language|Komering]]\n|script=[[Lampung script|Lampung]] (present)<br>[[Latin script|Latin]] (present)\n|lc1=ljp|ld1=Lampung Api\n|lc2=abl|ld2=Lampung Nyo\n|lc3=kge|ld3=Komering\n|glotto=lamp1241\n|glottorefname=Lampungic\n|map=Lampungic isolects.svg\n|mapcaption=The Lampungic varieties of southern Sumatra:\n{{legend|green|Lampung Api}}\n{{legend|red|Lampung Nyo}}\n{{legend|blue|Komering}}\n|notice=IPA\n}}\n\n'''Lampung''' or '''Lampungic''' (''cawa Lampung'') is an [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] language or [[dialect cluster]] with around 1.5 million [[native speaker]]s, who primarily belong to the [[Lampung people|Lampung]] ethnic group of southern [[Sumatra]], [[Indonesia]]. It is divided into two or three varieties: Lampung Api (also called Pesisir or A-dialect), Lampung Nyo (also called Abung or O-dialect), and Komering. The latter is sometimes included in Lampung Api, sometimes treated as an entirely separate language. [[Komering people]] see themselves as ethnically separate from, but related to, Lampung people.\n\nAlthough Lampung has a relatively large number of speakers, it is a minority language in the province of [[Lampung]], where most of the speakers live. Concerns over the endangerment of the language has led the provincial government to implement the teaching of Lampung language and [[Lampung script|script]] for primary and secondary education in the province.{{sfn|Katubi|2007|p=9}}\n\n==Classification==\n===External relationship===\nLampung is part of the [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] branch of [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] family, although its position within Malayo-Polynesian is hard to determine. Language contact over centuries has blurred the line between Lampung and Malay,{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=1}}{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=7\u20138}}{{sfn|Smith|2017|p=459}} to the extent that they were grouped into the same subfamily in older works, such as that of [[Isidore Dyen]] in 1965, in which Lampung is placed inside the \"Malayic Hesion\" alongside [[Malayan languages|Malayan]] ([[Malay language|Malay]], [[Minangkabau language|Minangkabau]], [[Kerinci language|Kerinci]]), [[Acehnese language|Acehnese]] and [[Madurese language|Madurese]].{{sfn|Dyen|1965|p=26}}\n\nNothofer (1985) separates Lampung from Dyen's Malayic, but still include it in the wider \"Javo-Sumatra Hesion\" alongside [[Malayic languages|Malayic]], [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]], Madurese, and more distantly, [[Javanese language|Javanese]].{{sfn|Nothofer|1985|p=298}} Ross (1995) assigns Lampung its own group, unclassified within Malayo-Polynesian.{{sfn|Ross|1995|pp=75, 78}} This position is followed by Adelaar (2005), who excludes Lampung from his [[Malayo-Sumbawan languages|Malayo-Sumbawan]] grouping\u2014which includes Sundanese, Madurese, and Malayo-Chamic-BSS (comprising Malayic,{{efn|The term \"Malayic\" has been defined differently by various linguists over time. Adelaar's Malayic roughly corresponds to Dyen's Malayan.}} [[Chamic languages|Chamic]], and [[Bali-Sasak-Sumbawa languages|Bali-Sasak-Sumbawa]] languages).{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=7\u20138}}{{sfn|Adelaar|2005|p=358}}\n\n[[File:Surat pantun cara Lampung.png|thumb|upright=1.2|left|A bilingual Lampung-Malay collection of poems, written in [[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]] and Lampung scripts]]\nAmong the Javo-Sumatran languages, Nothofer mentions that Sundanese is perhaps the closest to Lampung, as both languages share the development of [[Proto-Malayo-Polynesian]] (PMP) *R > ''y'' and the metathesis of the initial and medial consonants of [[Proto-Austronesian]] *lapaR > Sundanese ''palay'' 'desire, tired' and Lampung ''palay'' 'hurt of tired feet'.{{sfn|Nothofer|1985|p=298}} While the Javo-Sumatran/Malayo-Javanic grouping as a whole has been criticized or outright rejected by various linguists,{{sfn|Blust|1981}}{{sfn|Adelaar|2005|pp=357, 385}} a closer connection between Lampung and Sundanese has been supported by Anderbeck (2007), on the basis that both languages share more phonological developments with each other than with Adelaar's Malayo-Chamic-BSS.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=108\u2013110}}\n\nSmith (2017) notes that Lampung merges PMP *j with *d, which is a characteristic of his tentative [[Western Indonesian languages|Western Indonesian]] (WIn) subgroup.{{sfn|Smith|2017|p=456}} However, lexical evidence for its inclusion in WIn is scant. Smith identifies some WIn lexical innovations in Lampung, but it is hard to tell whether these words are inherited from Proto-WIn or borrowed later from Malay.{{sfn|Smith|2017|p=459}} While Smith supports its inclusion in the WIn subgroup, he states that the matter is still subject to debate.{{sfn|Smith|2017|p=459}}\n\n===Dialects===\n{{see also|Komering language}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float: right; margin: 1.2em\"\n|+ Lexical differences between Lampung dialects{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=1}}\n! English\n! Pesisir\n! Abung\n|-\n| fish\n| ''iwa''\n| ''punyu''\n|-\n| tooth\n| ''ipon''\n| ''kedis''\n|-\n| come\n| ''ratong''\n| ''megew''\n|}\n\nLampung dialects are most commonly classified according to their realizations of Proto-Lampungic final *a, which is retained in some varieties, but realized as [o] in others.{{sfn|Hanawalt|2007|p=31}}{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|p=22}} This dichotomy leads to the labeling of these as A-dialect and O-dialect, respectively.{{sfn|Matanggui|1984|p=63}} Walker (1975) uses the names Pesisir/Paminggir for the A-dialect and Abung for the O-dialect,{{sfn|Walker|1975|p=11}} but Matanggui (1984) argues that these are [[misnomer]]s, as each of them is more commonly associated with a specific [[tribe]] instead of the whole dialect group.{{sfn|Matanggui|1984|p=63}} Anderbeck and Hanawalt use the names \"Api\" for Pesisir and \"Nyo\" for Abung, after their respective words for \"what\".{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=7\u20138}} There are some lexical differences between these dialects,{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=1}} but they are identical in terms of morphology and syntax.{{sfn|Aliana|1986|p=66\u201367}}\n\nWalker (1976) further subdivides Abung into two subdialects: Abung and Menggala, while splitting the Pesisir group into four subdialects: Komering, Krui, Pubian, and Southern.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=1}} Aliana (1986) gives a different classification, listing a combined total of 13 different subdialects within both groups.{{sfn|Aliana|1986|p=47}} Through [[lexicostatistics|lexicostatistical]] analysis, Aliana finds that the Pesisir dialect of Talang Padang shares the most similarities with all dialects surveyed; in other words, it is the least divergent among Lampung varieties, while the Abung dialect of Jabung is the most divergent.{{sfn|Aliana|1986|p=66}} However, Aliana does not include Komering varieties in his survey of Lampung dialects, as he notes that some people do not consider it part of Lampung.{{sfn|Aliana|1986|pp=4, 45}}\n\nHanawalt (2007) largely agrees with Walker,{{sfn|Hanawalt|2007|pp=32, 34}} only that he classifies Nyo, Api, and Komering as separate languages rather than dialects of the same language based on sociological and linguistic criteria.{{sfn|Hanawalt|2007|p=35}} He notes that the biggest division is between the eastern (Nyo) and western (Api and Komering) varieties, with the latter forming an enormous [[dialect chain]] stretching from the southern tip of Sumatra up north to [[Komering River]] downstream. Some Lampungic-speaking groups (such as the Komering and Kayu Agung peoples) reject the \"Lampung\" label, although there is some understanding among them that they are \"ethnically related to the Lampung people of Lampung Province\".{{sfn|Hanawalt|2007|pp=32, 34}}  While many researchers consider Komering as part of Lampung Api, Hanawalt argues that there is enough linguistic and sociological differences to break down the western chain into two or more subdivisions; he thus proposes a Komering dialect chain, separate from Lampung Api.{{sfn|Hanawalt|2007|p=35}}\n\n==Demography and status==\nLike other [[languages of Indonesia|regional languages of Indonesia]], Lampung is not recognized as an [[official language]] anywhere in the country, and as such it is mainly used in informal situations.{{sfn|Amisani|1985|p=1}} Lampung is in vigorous use in rural areas where the Lampung ethnic group is the majority. A large percentage of speakers in these areas almost exclusively use Lampung at home, and use [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] on more formal occasions.{{sfn|Katubi|2007|p=4\u20135, 8\u20139}}{{sfn|Amisani|1985|p=7}} In the market where people of different backgrounds meet, a mix of languages is used, including local lingua franca like [[Musi language|Palembang Malay]].{{sfn|Katubi|2007|p=6}} In the 1970s, although Lampung was pretty much alive in rural areas, Lampung youths in urban areas already prefer to use Indonesian instead.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=1}} In general, there seems to be a trend of \"[[diglossia leakage]]\" in the bilingual Lampung communities, where Indonesian is increasingly used in domains traditionally associated with Lampung language usage.{{sfn|Katubi|2007|p=4\u20135, 8\u20139}}\n\n[[File:Tari Melinting 3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|right|A woman in Lampung traditional attire]]\nSince the early 20th century, the province of Lampung has been a major destination for the [[transmigration program]], which moves people from the more densely populated islands of Indonesia (then [[Dutch East Indies]]) to the less densely populated ones.{{sfn|Kusworo|2014|pp=23\u201324}}{{sfn|Aliana|1986|p=18}} The program came to a halt during an interlude following the outbreak of [[World War II]], but the government resumed it several years after [[Proclamation of Indonesian Independence|Indonesian independence]].{{sfn|Kusworo|2014|pp=23\u201324}} By the mid-1980s, Lampung people had become a minority in the province, accounting for no more than 15% of the population, down from 70% in 1920.{{sfn|Kusworo|2014|p=25}} This demographic shift is also reflected in language usage; the [[Indonesia 1980 census|1980 census]] reported that 78% of the province's population were native speakers of either Javanese, Sundanese, Madurese, or Balinese.{{sfn|Katubi|2007|pp=2\u20133}}\n\nAs an effort to maintain the indigenous language and \"to help define Lampung\u2019s identity and cultural symbol\", post-[[New Order (Indonesia)|New Order]] era Lampung regional government{{efn|The regional government of Lampung is still largely dominated by indigenous Lampung people, down to village level.{{sfn|Katubi|2007|pp=2\u20133}}}} has made Lampung language a compulsory subject for all students attending primary and secondary educational institutions across the province.{{sfn|Katubi|2007|pp=2\u20133}}{{sfn|Inawati|2017|pp=168\u2013169}} The [[Lampung University|state university of Lampung]] runs a [[master's degree]] program in Lampung language study.{{sfn|''Antaranews.com'' 17 October 2018}} The university once also held an [[associate degree]] in Lampung language study, but the program was temporarily halted in 2007 due to a change in regulation.{{sfn|Inawati|2017|pp=168\u2013169}} Nevertheless, the university has announced a plan to launch a [[bachelor's degree]] in Lampung language study by 2019.{{sfn|''Antaranews.com'' 17 October 2018}}\n\n==Phonology==\n===Vowels===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Basic vowels and diphthongs{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|p=16}}\n!\n! [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA link|i}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|u}}\n|-\n! [[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| ({{IPA link|e}})\n| {{IPAlink|\u0259}}\n| ({{IPA link|o}})\n|-\n! [[Open vowel|Open]]\n| \n| {{IPA link|a}}\n|\n|-\n! [[Diphthong]]s\n| colspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|aj &nbsp; aw &nbsp; uj &nbsp;}}\n|}\nAnderbeck distinguishes 4 basic vowel phonemes and 3 diphthongs in the Lampungic cluster. He prefers to analyze the {{IPA|/e/}} phoneme described by Walker{{sfn|Walker|1976|pp=3\u20134}} an allophone of {{IPA|/i/}}.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|p=16}} Similarly, he notes that the {{IPA|/o/}} phoneme previously posited for Komering by Abdurrahman and Yallop{{sfn|Abdurrahman|Yallop|1979|pp=11\u201312}} is better reanalyzed as an [[allophone]] of {{IPA|/\u0259/}}.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|p=16}} The reflection of {{IPA|/\u0259/}} varies widely across dialects, but the pattern is predictable. Western varieties consistently realize [[Ultima (linguistics)|ultimate]] {{IPA|/\u0259/}} as {{IPA|[o]}}; additionally, [[penultimate]] {{IPA|/\u0259/}} also becomes {{IPA|[o]}} in varieties spoken throughout the Komering river basin. In many Nyo dialects, final {{IPA|/\u0259/}} is reflected as an {{IPA|[o]}} or {{IPA|[a]}} if it is followed by {{IPA|/h/}} or {{IPA|/\u0294/}}. In the Nyo dialect of Blambangan Pagar, final {{IPA|/\u0259/}} is realized as {{IPA|[a]}} only if the previous vowel is also a schwa; otherwise, {{IPA|/\u0259/}} is realized as {{IPA|[\u0259]}}. The Melintin subdialect retains the conservative realization of *\u0259 as {{IPA|[\u0259]}} in all positions.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=17\u201319}}\n\nNyo varieties differ from the rest of Lampungic isolects by reflecting Proto-Lampungic final *a in open syllable as {{IPA|/o/}}.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=1}}{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|p=22}} Later, Nyo varieties also develop the tendency to realize final vowels as diphthongs. Final /o/ is variously realized as {{IPA|[\u0259\u0361\u0254]}}, {{IPA|[ow]}}, or similar diphthongs. Most Nyo speakers also pronounce final {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} as {{IPA|[\u0259j]}} and {{IPA|[\u0259w]}}, respectively.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|p=22}} This diphthongization of final vowels in open syllables occurs in all Nyo varieties, except in the Jabung subdialect.{{sfn|Hanawalt|2007|p=31}}\n\n===Consonants===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Basic consonants{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=14\u201315}}\n!\n! [[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPAlink|m}}\n| {{IPAlink|n}}\n| {{IPAlink|\u0272}}\n| {{IPAlink|\u014b}}\n|\n|-\n! [[Stop consonant|Stops]]\n| {{IPAlink|p}} &nbsp; {{IPAlink|b}}\n| {{IPAlink|t}} &nbsp; {{IPAlink|d}}\n| \n| {{IPAlink|k}} &nbsp; {{IPAlink|\u0261}}\n| {{IPAlink|\u0294}}\n|-\n! [[Fricative consonant|Fricatives]]\n| \n| {{IPAlink|s}} &nbsp; ({{IPAlink|z}})\n|\n| r{{efn|Represents the diverse reflections of Proto-Lampungic *r across dialects.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=14\u201315}}}}\n| {{IPAlink|h}}\n|-\n! [[Affricate consonant|Affricates]]\n| \n| \n| {{IPAlink|t\u0361\u0283}} &nbsp; {{IPAlink|d\u0361\u0292}}\n| \n| \n|-\n! [[Liquid consonant|Liquids]]\n| \n| {{IPAlink|l}}\n| \n| \n|\n|-\n! [[Semivowel]]s\n| {{IPAlink|w}}\n| \n| {{IPAlink|j}}\n|\n|\n|}\n\nThe occurrence of {{IPA|/z/}} is limited to some loanwords.{{sfn|Abdurrahman|Yallop|1979|pp=11\u201312}} There are various phonetic realizations of {{IPA|/r/}} within the Lampungic cluster, but it is usually a velar or uvular fricative ({{IPAlink|x|[x]}}, {{IPAlink|\u0263|[\u0263]}}, {{IPAlink|\u03c7|[\u03c7]}}, or {{IPAlink|\u0281|[\u0281]}}) in most dialects.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=14\u201315}} Udin (1992) includes this phoneme as {{IPA|/\u0263/}} and states that it is also variously pronounced as {{IPA|[x]}} or trilled {{IPAlink|r|[r]}}.{{sfn|Udin|1992|pp=4\u20135}} Walker lists {{IPA|/x/}} (with a voiced allophone {{IPA|[\u0263]}} between vocals) and {{IPA|/r/}} as separate phonemes for Way Lima subdialect, although he comments that the latter mostly appears in unassimilated loanwords, and is often interchangeable with {{IPA|[x]}}.{{sfn|Walker|1976|pp=3\u20134}} Abdurrahman and Yallop describe Komering {{IPA|/r/}} as an [[voiced alveolar trill|apical trill]] instead of a velar fricative.{{sfn|Abdurrahman|Yallop|1979|pp=11\u201312}}\n\nIn many varieties, some words have their consonants [[metathesis (linguistics)|metathesized]]. Examples include {{lang|ljp|hiru\u0294}} 'cloud' from Proto-Lampungic *rihu\u0294, {{lang|ljp|g\u0259ral}} \u2018name\u2019 from PLP *g\u0259lar,{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=14\u201315}} and the near-universal metathesis of PLP *hat\u0259luy (from PMP *qateluR) to {{lang|ljp|tahlui}} 'egg' or similar forms.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=62, 87\u201388}} Another common\u2013yet irregular\u2013phonological change in Lampungic cluster is [[debuccalization]], which occurs in almost all varieties. PLP *p and *t are often targets of debuccalization; *k is less affected by the change.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=14\u201315}}\n\nConsonant [[gemination]] is also common in Lampung, especially in Nyo and some Api varieties, but almost unknown in Komering. Gemination often happens to consonants preceded by penultimate schwa or historical voiceless nasal (which got reduced to the stop component). Cases of gemination in medial positions have been recorded for all consonants except {{IPA|/\u0272/}}, {{IPA|/\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/s/}}, {{IPA|/w/}} and {{IPA|/j/}}.{{sfn|Anderbeck|2007|pp=14\u201315}}\n\n===Phonotactics===\nThe most common syllable patterns are CV and CVC. [[Consonant cluster]]s are found in a few borrowed words, and only word-initially. These consonant clusters are also in free variation with sequences separated by schwas (CC~C\u0259C).{{sfn|Walker|1976|pp=3\u20134}} [[Disyllabic]] roots take the form (C)V.CV(C). Semivowels in medial positions are not contrastive with their absences.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=5}}\n\n===Stress===\nWords are always stressed in the [[ultima (linguistics)|final syllable]], regardless whether they are affixed or not. The stress though is very light and can be distorted by the overall phrasal [[Intonation (linguistics)|intonation]]. Partially free clitics, on the other hand, are never stressed except when they appear in the middle of an intonation contour.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=5}}\n\n==Grammar==\n===Pronouns===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Personal pronouns<br/>{{nobold|(Pesisir dialect)}}{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=2}}\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Meaning !! colspan=\"2\"|Independent<br/>pronoun !! rowspan=\"2\"|Clitic{{sfn|Udin|1992|pp=41\u201343}}\n|-\n! lower !! higher\n|-\n|{{gcl|1S|first person singular}} 'I' || ''nyak'' || ''saya'' || ''ku''=, =''ku''\n|-\n|{{gcl|2S|second person singular}} 'You (singular)' || ''niku'' || ''pusikam'' || =''mu''\n|-\n|{{gcl|3S|third person singular}} 'He/she' || ''ia'' || ''beliau'' || =''ni''\n|-\n|{{gcl|1P.EXCL|first person plural, exclusive}} 'We (exclusive)' || ''sikam'' || ''sikandua''{{efn|Also used as a polite counterpart of the first person singular pronoun.}} || \u2013 \n|-\n|{{gcl|1P.INCL|first person plural, inclusive}} 'We (inclusive)' || ''ram'' || ''ram'' || \u2013\n|-\n|{{gcl|2P|second person plural}} 'You (plural)' || ''kuti'' || ''pusikam'' || \u2013\n|-\n|{{gcl|3P|third person plural}} 'They' || ''tian'' || ''beliau'' || \u2013\n|}\n\nLike in some Indonesian languages, there is a distinction between the \"lower\" and \"higher\" forms of words based on the degrees of formality and the age or status of the speaker relative to the listener, although this distinction is only limited to pronouns and some words.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=2}} The \"lower\" forms are used when addressing younger people, or people with close relationship; while the \"higher\" forms are used when addressing older people or those with higher status.{{sfn|Udin|1992|pp=41\u201343}} Personal pronouns can act like [[proclitic]]s or free words. [[Enclitic]] pronouns are used to mark possession.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=5}} When speaking formally, the \"higher\" forms of pronouns are used instead of clitics.{{sfn|Udin|1992|pp=41\u201343}}\n\n===Reduplication===\nAs with many other Austronesian languages, [[reduplication]] is still a productive [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphological]] process in Lampung. Lampung has both full reduplication, which is the complete repetition of a [[morpheme]], and partial reduplication, which is the addition of a prefix to a morpheme consisting of its first consonant + {{IPA|/a/}}. Some morphemes are inherently reduplicated, such as {{lang|ljp|acang-acang}} 'pigeon' and {{lang|ljp|lalawah}} 'spider'.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=25}}\n\nNouns are fully reduplicated to indicate [[plural]]ity and variety, as in {{lang|ljp|sanak-sanak}} 'children' from {{lang|ljp|sanak}} 'child'{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=25}} and {{lang|abl|punyeu-punyeu}} 'fishes' from {{lang|abl|punyeu}} 'fish'.{{sfn|Wetty|1992|p=63\u201364}} Partial reduplication of nouns can convey the same meaning, but this formation is not as productive as full reduplication. More often, partial reduplication is used to signify a similarity between the root word and the derived noun:{{efn|Unless stated otherwise, all examples given in this and the following sections are taken from {{harvtxt|Walker|1976}}, with spelling adapted to {{harvtxt|Walker|1975}}, in which \u27e8e\u27e9 always represents {{IPA|[\u0259]}}, final \u27e8k\u27e9 represents {{IPA|[\u0294]}} (although some dialects contrast glottal stop with {{IPA|/k/}} in this position), and \u27e8r\u27e9 represents the various reflexes of {{IPA|/r/}} in the Lampung cluster. Fully reduplicated words are hyphenated for clarity.}}{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=25}}\n:{|\n| ||{{lang|ljp|baya}}||'flame'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|babaya}}||'coal (of a fire)'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|cupu}}||'a small cup (on a betel nut tray)'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|cacupu}}||'knee-cap'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|layang}}||'love letter (normally wafted across the room at a party)'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|lalayang}}||'kite'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|iwa lalayang}}||'a kind of flying fish'\n|-\n|}\n\nComplete reduplication of adjectives denotes intensification:{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=27}}{{sfn|Wetty|1992|p=66}}\n:{|\n| ||{{lang|ljp|balak-balak}}||'very large'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|geluk-geluk}}||'very fast'\n|}\n\nPartial reduplication, on the other hand, soften the meaning of an adjective:{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=27}}\n:{|\n| ||{{lang|ljp|rabay}}||'afraid'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|rarabay}}||'somewhat afraid'\n|}\n\nReduplication of verbs signifies \"a continuous or prolonged action or state\":{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=28}}\n:{|\n| ||{{lang|ljp|mengan-mengan}}||'eat all the time'\n|-\n| ||{{lang|ljp|maring-maring}}||'be continually sick'\n|}\n\n== Writing system==\n{{Main|Lampung script}}\n\n[[File:Enschede-Lampong letters by JA Schmidlin.jpg|thumb|right|Writing in Lampung script]]\nThe [[Latin script]] (with [[Indonesian orthography]]) is usually used for printed materials in the language.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=2}} However, traditionally, Lampung is written in its own script, an [[abugida]] or alphasyllabary, called {{lang|id|Aksara Lampung}} (in Indonesian) or {{lang|ljp|Had Lampung}} (in Lampung). It has 20 main characters and 13 diacritics.{{sfn|Junaidi et. al.|2013|p=664}} This script is most similar to the [[Rencong script|Kerinci]], [[Rejang script|Rejang]], and [[Batak script|Batak]] scripts used by various ethnic groups in the same island of Sumatra. All these scripts, alongside other traditional Indonesian writing systems like the [[Javanese script]], belong to the [[Brahmic scripts|Brahmic]] family of scripts that originated in India.{{sfn|Walker|1976|p=2}}\n\nLampung script has not yet been included in the Unicode standard as of 2019.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Komering language]]\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.endangeredalphabets.net/alphabets/lampung/ Lampung - Atlas of Endangered Alphabets]\n*[https://abvd.shh.mpg.de/austronesian/classification.php?node=Austronesian,%20Malayo-Polynesian,%20Lampung Wordlists for various Lampung dialects at Austronesian Basic Vocabulary Database]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|3}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Abdurrahman |first1=Sofjan |last2=Yallop |first2=Colin |date=1979 |chapter=A brief outline of Komering phonology and morphology |editor-last=Halim |editor-first=Amran |title=Miscellaneous Studies in Indonesian and Languages in Indonesia, Part VI |chapter-url=http://sealang.net/archives/nusa/pdf/nusa-v7-p11-18.pdf |series=NUSA: Linguistic Studies of Indonesian and Other Languages in Indonesia |volume=7 |pages=11\u201318 |location=Jakarta |publisher=Badan Penyelenggara Seri NUSA |access-date=5 May 2019 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Adelaar |first=Karl Alexander |title=Malayo-Sumbawan |journal=Oceanic Linguistics |volume=44 |issue=2 |date=2005 |pages=356\u2013388 |doi=10.1353/ol.2005.0027 |publisher=University of Hawai'i Press |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Aliana|first=Zainul Arifin|title=Ragam dan dialek bahasa Lampung|language=Indonesian|trans-title=Varieties and dialects of Lampung language|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7UYuAAAAMAAJ|year=1986|location=Jakarta |publisher=Pusat Pembinaan dan Pengembangan Bahasa, Departemen Pendidikan dan Kebudayaan}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Amisani|first1=Diana|title=Kedudukan dan fungsi bahasa Lampung|language=Indonesian|trans-title=The position and function of Lampung language|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-lK5AAAAIAAJ|year=1985|location=Jakarta |publisher=Pusat Pembinaan dan Pengembangan Bahasa, Departemen Pendidikan dan Kebudayaan}}\n* {{cite journal |last= Anderbeck|first=Karl Ronald |date=2007 |ti